---
import Layout from "@/layouts/Layout.astro";
import SectionHeading from "@/components/SectionHeading.astro";
---
<Layout
  title="Open source · Tournamental"
  description="Tournamental is 100% open source under Apache 2.0. The docs are CC-BY 4.0. Contributors share platform revenue via the Drips Network."
  ogImage="/og/open-source.png"
>
  <section class="container-page pt-16 pb-12">
    <SectionHeading
      eyebrow="Open source"
      title="100% open. Apache 2.0 code, CC-BY 4.0 docs."
      lede="Every line of code, every doc, every spec is on GitHub. Audit it. Fork it. Run your own. Contribute and share platform revenue via the Drips Network, not a stock-option pyramid, not a points scheme, real continuous USDC."
    />
    <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-3">
      <a href="https://github.com/0800tim/tournamental" class="btn-primary">View the repo</a>
      <a href="/contribute" class="btn-ghost">How to contribute</a>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="container-page pb-12">
    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-3 gap-6">
      <div class="card">
        <h3 class="font-bold text-white">Apache 2.0 (code)</h3>
        <p class="text-ink-200 mt-2">Permissive licence. Use it commercially. Fork it. Re-licence your changes if you want, the originals stay free.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card">
        <h3 class="font-bold text-white">CC-BY 4.0 (docs)</h3>
        <p class="text-ink-200 mt-2">Quote our docs. Translate them. Build courses around them. Just attribute.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card">
        <h3 class="font-bold text-white">Spec-first</h3>
        <p class="text-ink-200 mt-2">A canonical TypeScript message spec drives every producer and renderer. Build your own producer (StatsBomb, OPTA, an experiment of your own); we'll render it.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card">
        <h3 class="font-bold text-white">@tournamental/sdk</h3>
        <p class="text-ink-200 mt-2">Publishable npm package. Drop into any React app. <code>useMatchStream(id)</code> hook, <code>&lt;MatchScene /&gt;</code> R3F component, full typed API client.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card">
        <h3 class="font-bold text-white">@tournamental/mcp</h3>
        <p class="text-ink-200 mt-2">Model Context Protocol server. <code>npx @tournamental/mcp</code> in Claude Desktop or Cursor and you can spin up a syndicate, attach a tournament, or stream a match through your favourite LLM session.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card">
        <h3 class="font-bold text-white">Drips revenue share</h3>
        <p class="text-ink-200 mt-2">Platform revenue is split deterministically by merge-and-impact-weighted contribution. Quarterly payouts via the Drips Network. Opt in with a single registration step.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="container-prose pb-16">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white">Architecture, in 30 seconds</h2>
    <p class="prose-vt">Producers (StatsBomb-replay, mock-producer, future video-ingest) emit a canonical JSON message stream over WebSocket. Renderers (Next.js + React Three Fiber today; native apps and pixel-streaming later) consume that stream and render it. Every prediction is signed (VStamp), settled against the result, and reflected on global / country / syndicate leaderboards. Contributors and influencers earn revenue share through Drips and a partner program.</p>

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white mt-10">What's in the repo</h2>
    <ul class="prose-vt list-disc pl-6 space-y-2">
      <li><code>packages/spec/</code>, the canonical message spec.</li>
      <li><code>apps/statsbomb-replay/</code>, Python producer for any StatsBomb open-data match.</li>
      <li><code>apps/mock-producer/</code>, synthetic-match generator for development (<code>--out=ws|sse|file|stdout</code>).</li>
      <li><code>examples/hello-producer/</code> + <code>examples/hello-plugin-odds/</code>, ~50-line reference plugins. Fork to build a real data producer or odds source.</li>
      <li><code>packages/create-tournamental-app/</code>, the <code>npm create</code> scaffolder. <code>--template producer-ingest</code> spins up a typed plugin skeleton.</li>
      <li><code>apps/web/</code>, the Next.js + R3F renderer.</li>
      <li><code>packages/avatar/</code>, procedural avatars and the Wikidata-driven face billboard.</li>
      <li><code>packages/commentary/</code>, event templates + TTS scheduler.</li>
      <li><code>apps/api/</code>, Fastify API service.</li>
      <li><code>apps/marketing/</code>, this site.</li>
      <li><code>docs/</code>, 26 design docs covering vision, spec, renderer, producers, avatars, gamification, virality, and on-chain settlement.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white mt-10">Why we're doing this in the open</h2>
    <p class="prose-vt">Cultural infrastructure shouldn't be owned by a single company. The data formats and the renderers and the leaderboards should be standards that anyone can implement. Building Tournamental in the open means it survives us.</p>
    <p class="prose-vt">It also means the people who actually contribute, the engineer who writes the producer, the designer who improves the avatars, the analyst who tunes the IQ formula, get paid in proportion to what they build, continuously, on-chain, automatically.</p>
  </section>
</Layout>
